ocusing on the technologies that supplement and enhance human perception, Masiello looks at the evolution of what she calls “sense work” in cultural texts, mainly from Latin America, that wend from the heights of romantic thought to the startling innovations of modernism in the early twentieth century and then to times of posthuman experience when cyber bodies hurtle through globalized space and human senses are reproduced by machines. Tracing the shifting debates on perceptions, The Senses of Democracy offers a new paradigm with which to speak of Latin American cultural history and launches a field for the comparative study of bodies, experience, pleasure, and pain over the continental divide. In the end, sense work helps us to understand how culture finds its location.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aDemocracy in literature. 0aDemocracyzLatin America. 0aLiterature and societyzLatin America. 0aPolitics and culturezLatin America. 0aSenses and sensationxSocial aspects. 0aSocial changezLatin America. 0aSynesthesiaxSocial aspects. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/3503340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477315057423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477315057/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK